Knowledge can be made explicit by its holder, e.g. by reflection or discussion.
This explicit knowledge can be transmitted as information either verbally, physically (notes) or in digital form (so called _data entry_).
In the context of this pattern, this is one of the initial (or input-) knowledge for the remaining flow.
Once recorded there is a good chance to reproduce the initial knowledge, through the following flow, even if the initial knowledge would be lost later.

Information is always the (implicit) basis for data in any form (documents, records...). That is because documents and records encode information, ultimately in some physical way (e.g. dots of ink on paper, or magnetic state on disks or tape).
Therefore, data _*implements*_ the information which is contained in that data.
Information may be gathered from humans' knowledge. In that case, the *information* state is typically transient on its way from *knowledge* to *data* (while it gets _documented_ or _recorded_).
In more trivial cases, information is received from information systems via documents or records. Also in these cases the information state does not appear explicitly or technically. Often it can be recognized only in the schema (of records), the layout (of documents) or in a machine's algorithm.

Data in document form - either physical (e.g. printed paper) or digital (e.g. PDF file), typically meant for use by a human.
Records are machine-readable equivalents of documents.
Some machines can read some types of documents. In those cases it is typically a specialized machine (so called _reader_) for a particular type of document (e.g. _Adobe Reader_).
In the case of a digital document it is always a _machine_ (more precisely a *_system_* of hardware, software and an output device) through which a human can read the document. _Details of this case are left out from the diagram for clarity. These details can be represented as an expansion of the *edge* leading from *document* to *human*._

Records are technical structures for storing information.
Records are machine-readable equivalents of documents.
Records are typically read and processed by machines.
_Depending on the level of encoding, some higher-level records might by readable for humans if they can be serialized to text. Strictly that would be the case of a (text-)document with a structure that is very close to the record - but not the record itself._

An artificial agent, also known as a machine. The machine reads records and *_may_* decode them into information *_if_* that machine is designed for decoding these records (some machines are just designed to copy records with no higher level of decoding.
A machine *_might_* even acquire _knowledge_ from this information (depending on the capability of that machine and on our definition of knowledge).
Due to these eventualities, a machine that is capable of decoding information and acquiring knowledge is presented as a future thing here.
More typically a machine copies records or transforms them into records with different structure and/or content, or creates documents (images, text...) from records.
